{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1779196963180,"sessionID":"ses_1bf9f8fabffeWrpKfONbqDLERZ","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_01_Qwq8cpQLlYB1B9h2GQtk8226","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/saifulpotential/Potential/nestfind-sample/.claude/react/docs/auth-guards.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/saifulpotential/Potential/nestfind-sample/.claude/react/docs/auth-guards.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Authentication Guards\n2: \n3: ## Overview\n4: \n5: Route protection using 3 separate guard components and layout-level RBAC. Guards enforce authentication and role-based access control across route trees.\n6: \n7: > **Important:** The specific auth method (httpOnly cookies, Bearer tokens, sessions) and role names come from your project's PRD. This guide covers the structural patterns only.\n8: \n9: ---\n10: \n11: ## Role Contract (CRITICAL)\n12: \n13: Your auth system MUST be internally consistent about the type of `role` on the user object:\n14: \n15: - **Either** role is always a `number` (recommended for numeric enums), OR\n16: - role is always a `string` (recommended for string enums)\n17: \n18: **Never mix.** The JWT payload, the `/auth/login` response, the `/users/me` response, and the frontend `AuthUser` type must all agree. If they don't, `allowedRoles.includes(user.role)` fails silently and guards become permissive — a low-privilege user ends up able to view admin pages because `\"1\" !== 1` (or vice versa).\n19: \n20: Signs of role-type drift:\n21: - UI login for one role redirects to `/` (generic home) instead of the role-specific home\n22: - Chaos tests for role-gate protection fail intermittently\n23: - Guards render a flash of admin content before redirecting\n24: \n25: If you suspect drift in an existing project, the guards in this doc already normalize both sides via `String(...)` — but the better fix is at the backend JWT strategy. See `.claude/{$BACKEND}/guides/authentication-cookies.md` → \"Role coercion\".\n26: \n27: ---\n28: \n29: ## Guard Components\n30: \n31: ### 1. GuestGuard\n32: \n33: Protects auth pages (login, signup) — redirects authenticated users to their home route.\n34: \n35: Location: `~/components/guards/GuestGuard.tsx`\n36: \n37: ```typescript\n38: import { Navigate, Outlet } from 'react-router';\n39: import { useAuth } from '~/hooks/useAuth';\n40: import { Loader2 } from 'lucide-react';\n41: \n42: export function GuestGuard() {\n43:   const { isAuthenticated, authChecked } = useAuth();\n44: \n45:   if (!authChecked) {\n46:     return (\n47:       <div className=\"flex items-center justify-center h-screen\">\n48:         <Loader2 className=\"h-8 w-8 animate-spin text-muted-foreground\" />\n49:       </div>\n50:     );\n51:   }\n52: \n53:   if (isAuthenticated) {\n54:     return <Navigate to=\"/dashboard\" replace />;\n55:   }\n56: \n57:   return <Outlet />;\n58: }\n59: ```\n60: \n61: > GuestGuard renders `<Outlet />` (not `children`) because it is used as a **layout component** in the route config via `layout('pages/auth/layout.tsx', authRoutes)`.\n62: \n63: ### 2. AuthGuard\n64: \n65: Protects private routes — redirects unauthenticated users to login. Use for one-off component-level checks when inline RBAC in the layout isn't sufficient.\n66: \n67: Location: `~/components/guards/AuthGuard.tsx`\n68: \n69: ```typescript\n70: import { Navigate, Outlet } from 'react-router';\n71: import { useAuth } from '~/hooks/useAuth';\n72: import { Loader2 } from 'lucide-react';\n73: \n74: export function AuthGuard({ children }: { children?: React.ReactNode }) {\n75:   const { isAuthenticated, authChecked } = useAuth();\n76: \n77:   if (!authChecked) {\n78:     return (\n79:       <div className=\"flex items-center justify-center h-screen\">\n80:         <Loader2 className=\"h-8 w-8 animate-spin text-muted-foreground\" />\n81:       </div>\n82:     );\n83:   }\n84: \n85:   if (!isAuthenticated) {\n86:     return <Navigate to=\"/login\" replace />;\n87:   }\n88: \n89:   return children ? <>{children}</> : <Outlet />;\n90: }\n91: ```\n92: \n93: ### 3. RoleGuard\n94: \n95: Checks if user has one of the allowed roles — redirects to `/unauthorized` if not. Use for component-level role checks within a page.\n96: \n97: Location: `~/components/guards/RoleGuard.tsx`\n98: \n99: ```typescript\n100: import { Navigate, Outlet } from 'react-router';\n101: import { useAuth } from '~/hooks/useAuth';\n102: \n103: interface RoleGuardProps {\n104:   // Use a union of your project's Role enum values (numeric or string — be consistent)\n105:   allowedRoles: Array<string | number>;\n106:   children?: React.ReactNode;\n107: }\n108: \n109: export function RoleGuard({ allowedRoles, children }: RoleGuardProps) {\n110:   const { user, isAuthenticated } = useAuth();\n111: \n112:   if (!isAuthenticated || !user) {\n113:     return <Navigate to=\"/login\" replace />;\n114:   }\n115: \n116:   // Normalize both sides to string so number-vs-string role contracts don't silently fail.\n117:   // See \"Role Contract\" section above.\n118:   const allowed = allowedRoles.map(String).includes(String(user.role));\n119:   if (!allowed) {\n120:     return <Navigate to=\"/unauthorized\" replace />;\n121:   }\n122: \n123:   return children ? <>{children}</> : <Outlet />;\n124: }\n125: ```\n126: \n127: ---\n128: \n129: ## Guard Props Summary\n130: \n131: | Guard | Props | Purpose |\n132: |-------|-------|---------|\n133: | `GuestGuard` | none (renders `<Outlet />`) | Auth pages only — redirects logged-in users |\n134: | `AuthGuard` | `{ children?: ReactNode }` | Protected pages — redirects unauthenticated users |\n135: | `RoleGuard` | `{ allowedRoles: string[], children?: ReactNode }` | Role-specific — redirects wrong role to `/unauthorized` |\n136: \n137: ---\n138: \n139: ## Layout-Level Protection Pattern (Recommended)\n140: \n141: The recommended pattern is to **inline auth + RBAC checks directly in the layout component**, rather than wrapping layouts with guards. This gives the layout full control over loading states, redirects, and UI.\n142: \n143: ### Protected Layout with Inline RBAC\n144: \n145: ```typescript\n146: // ~/components/layouts/ProtectedLayout.tsx\n147: import { Outlet, Navigate, useLocation } from 'react-router';\n148: import { useAuth } from '~/hooks/useAuth';\n149: import { Sidebar } from '~/components/layout/Sidebar';\n150: import Header from '~/components/layout/Header';\n151: import { Loader2 } from 'lucide-react';\n152: \n153: // RBAC route access map — populate from your PRD.\n154: // Use your project's Role enum. Both sides are stringified at compare time to\n155: // defend against number-vs-string drift between the JWT payload and the enum.\n156: const routeAccess: Record<string, Array<string | number>> = {\n157:   '/dashboard': ['admin', 'user'],\n158:   '/users': ['admin'],\n159:   '/items': ['admin', 'user'],\n160:   '/settings': ['admin'],\n161:   '/profile': ['admin', 'user'],\n162:   // Add routes and allowed roles from your PRD\n163: };\n164: \n165: export default function ProtectedLayout() {\n166:   const { isAuthenticated, authChecked, user } = useAuth();\n167:   const location = useLocation();\n168: \n169:   // 1. Loading state — prevent flash of wrong content\n170:   if (!authChecked) {\n171:     return (\n172:       <div className=\"flex h-screen items-center justify-center\">\n173:         <Loader2 className=\"h-8 w-8 animate-spin text-primary\" />\n174:       </div>\n175:     );\n176:   }\n177: \n178:   // 2. Auth check — redirect to login if not authenticated\n179:   if (!isAuthenticated || !user) {\n180:     return <Navigate to=\"/login\" replace />;\n181:   }\n182: \n183:   // 3. RBAC check — verify user role has access to current route.\n184:   // Stringify both sides to avoid number-vs-string drift (see Role Contract).\n185:   const currentPath = '/' + location.pathname.split('/').filter(Boolean)[0];\n186:   const allowedRoles = routeAccess[currentPath];\n187:   if (allowedRoles && !allowedRoles.map(String).includes(String(user.role))) {\n188:     return <Navigate to=\"/unauthorized\" replace />;\n189:   }\n190: \n191:   // 4. Render layout with protected content\n192:   return (\n193:     <div className=\"flex h-screen\">\n194:       <Sidebar />\n195:       <div className=\"flex-1 flex flex-col min-h-0 overflow-hidden\">\n196:         <Header />\n197:         <main className=\"flex-1 overflow-y-auto p-4 md:p-6\">\n198:           <Outlet />\n199:         </main>\n200:       </div>\n201:     </div>\n202:   );\n203: }\n204: ```\n205: \n206: ### Auth Layout (Guest-Only)\n207: \n208: ```typescript\n209: // ~/pages/auth/layout.tsx\n210: import { GuestGuard } from '~/components/guards/GuestGuard';\n211: \n212: export default function AuthLayout() {\n213:   return <GuestGuard />;\n214: }\n215: ```\n216: \n217: > The auth layout delegates entirely to `GuestGuard`, which handles loading, redirect, and renders `<Outlet />` for guest users.\n218: \n219: ---\n220: \n221: ## Guard Decision Matrix\n222: \n223: | Route Type | Protection Method | `!authChecked` | `!isAuthenticated` | Wrong Role |\n224: |------------|-------------------|----------------|--------------------|-----------|\n225: | Public (/, /about) | None | N/A | N/A | N/A |\n226: | Auth (/login, /signup) | `GuestGuard` in auth layout | Spinner | Allow | N/A |\n227: | Protected (/dashboard/*) | Inline in `ProtectedLayout` | Spinner | → /login | → /unauthorized |\n228: \n229: ---\n230: \n231: ## Auth State Hook\n232: \n233: Guards depend on a `useAuth()` hook that abstracts the auth state source (Redux or Context):\n234: \n235: ```typescript\n236: // ~/hooks/useAuth.ts\n237: import type { AuthState } from '~/types/auth';\n238: \n239: // Implementation: connect to your auth store (Redux or Context)\n240: export function useAuth(): AuthState {\n241:   // Option A: Redux\n242:   // const { user, isAuthenticated, authChecked } = useSelector((state: RootState) => state.auth);\n243: \n244:   // Option B: Context\n245:   // const { user, isAuthenticated, authChecked } = useContext(AuthContext);\n246: \n247:   return { user, isAuthenticated, authChecked };\n248: }\n249: ```\n250: \n251: ### Key State Flags\n252: \n253: - **authChecked**: Set to `true` after initial auth check completes (success or failure). Prevents premature redirects.\n254: - **isAuthenticated**: `true` when user is logged in\n255: - **user**: Contains user object with `role` field for RBAC\n256: \n257: ---\n258: \n259: ## When to Use Standalone Guards vs Inline Layout\n260: \n261: | Scenario | Approach |\n262: |----------|----------|\n263: | Entire route group needs auth + RBAC | **Inline in layout** (recommended) |\n264: | Auth pages (login, signup) | **GuestGuard** as layout |\n265: | One-off route needing extra role check | **RoleGuard** wrapping page content |\n266: | Component-level permission check | **RoleGuard** wrapping specific UI section |\n267: \n268: ---\n269: \n270: ## Best Practices\n271: \n272: ### DO\n273: \n274: - Use inline auth + RBAC checks in layout components (single responsibility)\n275: - Show loading spinner during auth check (prevent flash of content)\n276: - Use `replace: true` on `<Navigate>` to prevent back-button issues\n277: - Check auth BEFORE checking role\n278: - Use the `authChecked` flag to prevent premature redirects\n279: - Define `routeAccess` map from your PRD's role definitions\n280: \n281: ### DON'T\n282: \n283: - Guard every individual page component separately\n284: - Skip loading state (causes flash of wrong content)\n285: - Redirect without `replace` (creates broken history)\n286: - Check role without checking authentication first\n287: - Hardcode role names — derive from your project's PRD/enums\n288: \n289: ---\n290: \n291: ## Implementation Checklist\n292: \n293: When implementing auth guards:\n294: \n295: 1. [ ] `useAuth()` hook created (connecting to Redux or Context)\n296: 2. [ ] `GuestGuard` component created (renders `<Outlet />`)\n297: 3. [ ] `AuthGuard` component created (for one-off use)\n298: 4. [ ] `RoleGuard` component created (for one-off use)\n299: 5. [ ] `ProtectedLayout` has inline auth + RBAC with `routeAccess` map\n300: 6. [ ] Auth layout uses `<GuestGuard />` as its content\n301: 7. [ ] `authChecked` flag set after initial auth check\n302: 8. [ ] Loading spinner shown during auth check\n303: 9. [ ] Redirects use `replace: true`\n304: 10. [ ] `/unauthorized` page exists for role mismatch\n305: \n306: ---\n307: \n308: ## Related Files\n309: \n310: - [routing-guide.md](./routing-guide.md) — Route configuration patterns\n311: - [authentication-architecture.md](./authentication-architecture.md) — Auth flow and state management\n312: - [file-organization.md](./file-organization.md) — Directory structure\n313: - `~/components/guards/GuestGuard.tsx` — Guest guard (renders Outlet)\n314: - `~/components/guards/AuthGuard.tsx` — Auth guard\n315: - `~/components/guards/RoleGuard.tsx` — Role guard\n316: - `~/components/layouts/ProtectedLayout.tsx` — Protected layout with inline RBAC\n317: - `~/hooks/useAuth.ts` — Auth state hook\n\n(End of file - total 317 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Authentication Guards\n\n## Overview\n\nRoute protection using 3 separate guard components and layout-level RBAC. Guards enforce authentication and role-based access control across route trees.\n\n> **Important:** The specific auth method (httpOnly cookies, Bearer tokens, sessions) and role names come from your project's PRD. This guide covers the structural patterns only.\n\n---\n\n## Role Contract (CRITICAL)\n\nYour auth system MUST be internally consistent about the type of `role` on the user object:\n\n- **Either** role is always a `number` (recommended for numeric enums), OR\n- role is always a `string` (recommended for string enums)\n\n**Never mix.** The JWT payload, the `/auth/login` response, the `/users/me` response, and the frontend `AuthUser` type must all agree. If they don't, `allowedRoles.includes(user.role)` fails silently and guards become permissive — a low-privilege user ends up able to view admin pages because `\"1\" !== 1` (or vice versa).\n\nSigns of role-type drift:","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":".claude/react/docs/auth-guards.md","time":{"start":1779196962899,"end":1779196963178}},"id":"prt_e4067234e001SYU9qzcohohNP6","sessionID":"ses_1bf9f8fabffeWrpKfONbqDLERZ","messageID":"msg_e40665684001CLexdMdAguT4AF"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1779196965047,"sessionID":"ses_1bf9f8fabffeWrpKfONbqDLERZ","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_02_PTJpbjK1m92TYYuToF405760","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/saifulpotential/Potential/nestfind-sample/.claude/react/docs/i18n-architecture.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/saifulpotential/Potential/nestfind-sample/.claude/react/docs/i18n-architecture.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # i18n Architecture Guide\n2: \n3: ## Overview\n4: \n5: When a project requires multilingual support, use `react-i18next` for internationalization.\n6: \n7: ---\n8: \n9: ## Setup\n10: \n11: ### 1. Install Dependencies\n12: \n13: ```bash\n14: npm install react-i18next i18next i18next-http-backend i18next-browser-languagedetector\n15: ```\n16: \n17: ### 2. Create i18n Configuration\n18: \n19: ```typescript\n20: // app/i18n.ts\n21: import i18n from 'i18next';\n22: import { initReactI18next } from 'react-i18next';\n23: import LanguageDetector from 'i18next-browser-languagedetector';\n24: import Backend from 'i18next-http-backend';\n25: \n26: i18n\n27:   .use(Backend)\n28:   .use(LanguageDetector)\n29:   .use(initReactI18next)\n30:   .init({\n31:     fallbackLng: 'en',\n32:     supportedLngs: ['en', 'ko'],\n33:     defaultNS: 'translation',\n34:     interpolation: {\n35:       escapeValue: false, // React already escapes\n36:     },\n37:     backend: {\n38:       loadPath: '/locales/{{lng}}/{{ns}}.json',\n39:     },\n40:   });\n41: \n42: export default i18n;\n43: ```\n44: \n45: ### 3. Create Locale Files\n46: \n47: ```\n48: public/\n49: └── locales/\n50:     ├── en/\n51:     │   └── translation.json\n52:     └── ko/\n53:         └── translation.json\n54: ```\n55: \n56: ```json\n57: // public/locales/en/translation.json\n58: {\n59:   \"common\": {\n60:     \"save\": \"Save\",\n61:     \"cancel\": \"Cancel\",\n62:     \"delete\": \"Delete\",\n63:     \"loading\": \"Loading...\",\n64:     \"noResults\": \"No results found\",\n65:     \"error\": \"Something went wrong\"\n66:   },\n67:   \"auth\": {\n68:     \"login\": \"Login\",\n69:     \"logout\": \"Logout\",\n70:     \"email\": \"Email\",\n71:     \"password\": \"Password\"\n72:   }\n73: }\n74: ```\n75: \n76: ### 4. Initialize in Entry Point\n77: \n78: ```typescript\n79: // root.tsx\n80: import './i18n';\n81: ```\n82: \n83: ---\n84: \n85: ## Usage in Components\n86: \n87: ### Basic Translation\n88: \n89: ```typescript\n90: import { useTranslation } from 'react-i18next';\n91: \n92: export const SaveButton = () => {\n93:   const { t } = useTranslation();\n94:   return <button>{t('common.save')}</button>;\n95: };\n96: ```\n97: \n98: ### With Variables\n99: \n100: ```typescript\n101: // translation.json: \"welcome\": \"Hello, {{name}}!\"\n102: <p>{t('welcome', { name: user.name })}</p>\n103: ```\n104: \n105: ### Plurals\n106: \n107: ```typescript\n108: // translation.json: \"items_one\": \"{{count}} item\", \"items_other\": \"{{count}} items\"\n109: <span>{t('items', { count: itemCount })}</span>\n110: ```\n111: \n112: ---\n113: \n114: ## Language Switcher\n115: \n116: ```typescript\n117: import { useTranslation } from 'react-i18next';\n118: \n119: export const LanguageSwitcher = () => {\n120:   const { i18n } = useTranslation();\n121: \n122:   return (\n123:     <select\n124:       value={i18n.language}\n125:       onChange={(e) => i18n.changeLanguage(e.target.value)}\n126:     >\n127:       <option value=\"en\">English</option>\n128:       <option value=\"ko\">한국어</option>\n129:     </select>\n130:   );\n131: };\n132: ```\n133: \n134: ---\n135: \n136: ## MANDATORY Rules\n137: \n138: - **Every visible string** in UI components MUST use `t()` — no hardcoded text\n139: - **Locale files** must exist for ALL supported languages before shipping\n140: - **Keys** use dot notation organized by feature: `auth.login`, `dashboard.title`\n141: - **Fallback language** must always be set (typically `en`)\n142: - **Do NOT** use string concatenation for translated strings — use interpolation variables\n143: - **Form validation messages** should also be translated via Zod `.refine()` with `t()`\n144: \n145: ## E2E Testing with i18n\n146: \n147: When writing Playwright tests for i18n apps:\n148: - Use `[data-testid]` selectors (language-independent) — preferred\n149: - Or bilingual regex: `button:has-text(/Save|저장/i)`\n150: - NEVER use English-only text selectors when default locale is not English\n151: \n152: ---\n153: \n154: ## Related\n155: \n156: - [best-practices.md](best-practices.md) — Coding standards\n157: - [component-patterns.md](component-patterns.md) — Component structure\n158: - [typescript-standards.md](typescript-standards.md) — Type safety\n\n(End of file - total 158 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# i18n Architecture Guide\n\n## Overview\n\nWhen a project requires multilingual support, use `react-i18next` for internationalization.\n\n---\n\n## Setup\n\n### 1. Install Dependencies\n\n```bash\nnpm install react-i18next i18next i18next-http-backend i18next-browser-languagedetector\n```\n\n### 2. Create i18n Configuration\n\n```typescript\n// app/i18n.ts","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":".claude/react/docs/i18n-architecture.md","time":{"start":1779196964683,"end":1779196965045}},"id":"prt_e406729e000174gqxV5COLeqER","sessionID":"ses_1bf9f8fabffeWrpKfONbqDLERZ","messageID":"msg_e40665684001CLexdMdAguT4AF"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1779196966789,"sessionID":"ses_1bf9f8fabffeWrpKfONbqDLERZ","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_03_qMuH6B8BjrZDC4fBnqIC5801","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/saifulpotential/Potential/nestfind-sample/.claude/react/docs/component-patterns.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/saifulpotential/Potential/nestfind-sample/.claude/react/docs/component-patterns.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Component Patterns\n2: \n3: Modern component architecture using Shadcn/UI, Tailwind CSS, and TypeScript.\n4: \n5: ---\n6: \n7: ## Function Component Pattern (PREFERRED)\n8: \n9: ### Why Function Components\n10: \n11: All components use function components with TypeScript for:\n12: \n13: - Explicit type safety for props\n14: - Consistent component signatures\n15: - Clear prop interface documentation\n16: - Better IDE autocomplete\n17: \n18: ### Basic Pattern\n19: \n20: ```typescript\n21: import { Button } from '~/components/ui/button';\n22: import { cn } from '~/lib/utils';\n23: \n24: interface MyComponentProps {\n25:   /** User ID to display */\n26:   userId: number;\n27:   /** Optional callback when action occurs */\n28:   onAction?: () => void;\n29: }\n30: \n31: export default function MyComponent({ userId, onAction }: MyComponentProps) {\n32:   return (\n33:     <div className=\"p-4\">\n34:       User: {userId}\n35:       <Button onClick={onAction}>Action</Button>\n36:     </div>\n37:   );\n38: }\n39: ```\n40: \n41: **Key Points:**\n42: \n43: - Props interface defined separately with JSDoc comments\n44: - Destructure props in parameters\n45: - Default export at bottom\n46: - Use Tailwind classes for styling\n47: \n48: ---\n49: \n50: ## Shadcn/UI Component Usage\n51: \n52: ### Available Components\n53: \n54: Shadcn/UI components are in `~/components/ui/`:\n55: \n56: ```typescript\n57: // Buttons\n58: import { Button, buttonVariants } from '~/components/ui/button';\n59: \n60: // Forms\n61: import { Input } from '~/components/ui/input';\n62: import { Label } from '~/components/ui/label';\n63: import {\n64:   Form,\n65:   FormControl,\n66:   FormField,\n67:   FormItem,\n68:   FormLabel,\n69:   FormMessage,\n70: } from '~/components/ui/form';\n71: \n72: // Cards\n73: import { Card, CardContent, CardHeader, CardTitle } from '~/components/ui/card';\n74: ```\n75: \n76: ### Button Component\n77: \n78: ```typescript\n79: import { Button } from '~/components/ui/button';\n80: \n81: // Variants\n82: <Button variant=\"default\">Primary</Button>\n83: <Button variant=\"secondary\">Secondary</Button>\n84: <Button variant=\"destructive\">Delete</Button>\n85: <Button variant=\"outline\">Outlined</Button>\n86: <Button variant=\"ghost\">Ghost</Button>\n87: <Button variant=\"link\">Link</Button>\n88: \n89: // Sizes\n90: <Button size=\"sm\">Small</Button>\n91: <Button size=\"default\">Default</Button>\n92: <Button size=\"lg\">Large</Button>\n93: <Button size=\"icon\"><Icon /></Button>\n94: \n95: // States\n96: <Button disabled>Disabled</Button>\n97: <Button className=\"w-full\">Full Width</Button>\n98: ```\n99: \n100: ### Card Component\n101: \n102: ```typescript\n103: import { Card, CardContent, CardHeader, CardTitle } from '~/components/ui/card';\n104: \n105: <Card className=\"w-full max-w-md\">\n106:   <CardHeader>\n107:     <CardTitle>Card Title</CardTitle>\n108:   </CardHeader>\n109:   <CardContent className=\"space-y-4\">\n110:     <p>Card content goes here</p>\n111:   </CardContent>\n112: </Card>\n113: ```\n114: \n115: ### Form Components (MANDATORY PATTERN — all forms must use this)\n116: \n117: ```typescript\n118: import { useForm } from 'react-hook-form';\n119: import { zodResolver } from '@hookform/resolvers/zod';\n120: import { z } from 'zod';\n121: import { Button } from '~/components/ui/button';\n122: import { Input } from '~/components/ui/input';\n123: import {\n124:   Form,\n125:   FormControl,\n126:   FormField,\n127:   FormItem,\n128:   FormLabel,\n129:   FormMessage,\n130: } from '~/components/ui/form';\n131: \n132: const schema = z.object({\n133:   email: z.string().email(),\n134:   password: z.string().min(6),\n135: });\n136: \n137: type FormData = z.infer<typeof schema>;\n138: \n139: export default function LoginForm() {\n140:   const form = useForm<FormData>({\n141:     resolver: zodResolver(schema),\n142:     defaultValues: { email: '', password: '' },\n143:   });\n144: \n145:   return (\n146:     <Form {...form}>\n147:       <form onSubmit={form.handleSubmit(onSubmit)} className=\"space-y-4\">\n148:         <FormField\n149:           control={form.control}\n150:           name=\"email\"\n151:           render={({ field }) => (\n152:             <FormItem>\n153:               <FormLabel>Email</FormLabel>\n154:               <FormControl>\n155:                 <Input placeholder=\"Enter email\" {...field} />\n156:               </FormControl>\n157:               <FormMessage />\n158:             </FormItem>\n159:           )}\n160:         />\n161:         <Button type=\"submit\">Submit</Button>\n162:       </form>\n163:     </Form>\n164:   );\n165: }\n166: ```\n167: \n168: ---\n169: \n170: ## CVA (Class Variance Authority)\n171: \n172: ### What is CVA\n173: \n174: CVA is used for component variants in Shadcn/UI. It creates type-safe variant props.\n175: \n176: ### Example from Button Component\n177: \n178: ```typescript\n179: import { cva, type VariantProps } from 'class-variance-authority';\n180: import { cn } from '~/lib/utils';\n181: \n182: const buttonVariants = cva(\n183:   // Base styles applied to all buttons\n184:   'inline-flex items-center justify-center rounded-md text-sm font-medium transition-all',\n185:   {\n186:     variants: {\n187:       variant: {\n188:         default: 'bg-primary text-primary-foreground hover:bg-primary/90',\n189:         destructive: 'bg-destructive text-white hover:bg-destructive/90',\n190:         outline: 'border bg-background hover:bg-accent',\n191:         secondary: 'bg-secondary text-secondary-foreground hover:bg-secondary/80',\n192:         ghost: 'hover:bg-accent hover:text-accent-foreground',\n193:         link: 'text-primary underline-offset-4 hover:underline',\n194:       },\n195:       size: {\n196:         default: 'h-9 px-4 py-2',\n197:         sm: 'h-8 px-3',\n198:         lg: 'h-10 px-6',\n199:         icon: 'size-9',\n200:       },\n201:     },\n202:     defaultVariants: {\n203:       variant: 'default',\n204:       size: 'default',\n205:     },\n206:   }\n207: );\n208: \n209: // Usage in component\n210: function Button({\n211:   className,\n212:   variant,\n213:   size,\n214:   ...props\n215: }: React.ComponentProps<'button'> & VariantProps<typeof buttonVariants>) {\n216:   return (\n217:     <button\n218:       className={cn(buttonVariants({ variant, size, className }))}\n219:       {...props}\n220:     />\n221:   );\n222: }\n223: ```\n224: \n225: ---\n226: \n227: ## When to Add a Variant vs Use className (MANDATORY)\n228: \n229: All reusable components must follow these rules:\n230: \n231: 1. **Every reusable component MUST accept a `className` prop** — this allows call-site-specific layout overrides\n232: 2. **Add a cva variant when:**\n233:    - The style combination appears at 2+ call sites\n234:    - It represents a semantic state (error, success, warning, loading, ghost, compact)\n235:    - It changes the visual identity of the component (not just layout)\n236: 3. **Use `className` when:**\n237:    - The override is context-specific and used at only 1 call site\n238:    - It's a layout concern (width, height, padding offset, positioning)\n239:    - It's a dynamic value passed from props (e.g., `className={style.text}`)\n240: \n241: ```typescript\n242: // ✅ CORRECT — Semantic state as variant\n243: <Input variant=\"error\" />\n244: \n245: // ✅ CORRECT — One-off layout as className\n246: <Input className=\"pl-10\" />\n247: \n248: // ❌ WRONG — Duplicated error classes at call sites\n249: <Input className=\"border-red-400 focus:ring-2 focus:ring-red-500/20\" />\n250: \n251: // ❌ WRONG — Creating a new component for a style difference\n252: // Instead, add a variant to the existing component\n253: ```\n254: \n255: ---\n256: \n257: ## cn() Utility for Class Merging\n258: \n259: ### What is cn()\n260: \n261: `cn()` combines `clsx` and `tailwind-merge` for conditional class merging:\n262: \n263: ```typescript\n264: // ~/lib/utils.ts\n265: import { clsx, type ClassValue } from 'clsx';\n266: import { twMerge } from 'tailwind-merge';\n267: \n268: export function cn(...inputs: ClassValue[]) {\n269:   return twMerge(clsx(inputs));\n270: }\n271: ```\n272: \n273: ### Usage Examples\n274: \n275: ```typescript\n276: import { cn } from '~/lib/utils';\n277: \n278: // Conditional classes\n279: <div className={cn(\n280:   'p-4 bg-background',\n281:   isActive && 'bg-primary text-primary-foreground',\n282:   isDisabled && 'opacity-50 pointer-events-none'\n283: )} />\n284: \n285: // Merging with overrides\n286: <Button className={cn(\n287:   buttonVariants({ variant: 'default' }),\n288:   'w-full' // Override width\n289: )} />\n290: \n291: // Array of conditions\n292: <div className={cn([\n293:   'base-class',\n294:   condition1 && 'class-1',\n295:   condition2 && 'class-2',\n296: ])} />\n297: ```\n298: \n299: ---\n300: \n301: ## asChild Pattern (Radix UI)\n302: \n303: ### What is asChild\n304: \n305: The `asChild` prop allows composing components with custom elements:\n306: \n307: ```typescript\n308: import { Button } from '~/components/ui/button';\n309: import { Link } from 'react-router';\n310: \n311: // Button as Link\n312: <Button asChild>\n313:   <Link to=\"/dashboard\">Go to Dashboard</Link>\n314: </Button>\n315: \n316: // Button as anchor\n317: <Button asChild variant=\"link\">\n318:   <a href=\"https://example.com\">External Link</a>\n319: </Button>\n320: ```\n321: \n322: ### How it Works\n323: \n324: The Button uses Radix's `Slot` component:\n325: \n326: ```typescript\n327: import { Slot } from '@radix-ui/react-slot';\n328: \n329: function Button({ asChild = false, ...props }) {\n330:   const Comp = asChild ? Slot : 'button';\n331:   return <Comp {...props} />;\n332: }\n333: ```\n334: \n335: ### IMPORTANT: asChild + Link Anti-Pattern\n336: \n337: **NEVER use `asChild` with `Link` inside `DropdownMenuItem`:**\n338: \n339: ```typescript\n340: // ❌ CAUSES VISUAL \"BLINK\" ON FIRST RENDER\n341: <DropdownMenuItem asChild>\n342:   <Link to={`/dashboard/users/${user.id}`}>\n343:     <Eye className=\"mr-2 h-4 w-4\" />\n344:     View Details\n345:   </Link>\n346: </DropdownMenuItem>\n347: \n348: // ✅ USE onClick with navigate() INSTEAD\n349: <DropdownMenuItem onClick={() => navigate(`/dashboard/users/${user.id}`)}>\n350:   <Eye className=\"mr-2 h-4 w-4\" />\n351:   View Details\n352: </DropdownMenuItem>\n353: ```\n354: \n355: **Better: Use the ActionMenu Component**\n356: \n357: For table action menus, use the reusable `ActionMenu` component:\n358: \n359: ```typescript\n360: import { ActionMenu } from '~/components/ui/action-menu';\n361: \n362: <ActionMenu\n363:   items={[\n364:     {\n365:       label: 'View Details',\n366:       icon: <Eye className=\"mr-2 h-4 w-4\" />,\n367:       href: `/dashboard/users/${user.id}`,  // Uses navigate() internally\n368:     },\n369:     {\n370:       label: 'Delete',\n371:       icon: <Trash2 className=\"mr-2 h-4 w-4\" />,\n372:       onClick: () => handleDelete(user.id),\n373:       variant: 'destructive',\n374:     },\n375:   ]}\n376: />\n377: ```\n378: \n379: ---\n380: \n381: ## Component Structure Template\n382: \n383: ### Recommended Order\n384: \n385: ```typescript\n386: import { useState, useCallback, useMemo, useEffect } from 'react';\n387: import { Link } from 'react-router';\n388: \n389: // Redux\n390: import { useAppDispatch, useAppSelector } from '~/redux/store/hooks';\n391: \n392: // UI Components\n393: import { Button } from '~/components/ui/button';\n394: import { Card, CardContent, CardHeader } from '~/components/ui/card';\n395: \n396: // Utilities\n397: import { cn } from '~/lib/utils';\n398: \n399: // Types\n400: import type { User } from '~/types/user';\n401: \n402: // 1. PROPS INTERFACE (with JSDoc)\n403: interface MyComponentProps {\n404:   /** The ID of the entity to display */\n405:   entityId: number;\n406:   /** Optional callback when action completes */\n407:   onComplete?: () => void;\n408:   /** Display mode */\n409:   mode?: 'view' | 'edit';\n410: }\n411: \n412: // 2. COMPONENT DEFINITION\n413: export default function MyComponent({\n414:   entityId,\n415:   onComplete,\n416:   mode = 'view',\n417: }: MyComponentProps) {\n418:   // 3. HOOKS (in this order)\n419:   // - Redux hooks\n420:   const dispatch = useAppDispatch();\n421:   const user = useAppSelector((state) => state.user.currentUser);\n422:   const loading = useAppSelector((state) => state.user.loading);\n423: \n424:   // - Local state\n425:   const [selectedItem, setSelectedItem] = useState<string | null>(null);\n426:   const [isEditing, setIsEditing] = useState(mode === 'edit');\n427: \n428:   // - Memoized values\n429:   const filteredData = useMemo(() => {\n430:     return data.filter((item) => item.active);\n431:   }, [data]);\n432: \n433:   // - Effects\n434:   useEffect(() => {\n435:     // Setup\n436:     return () => {\n437:       // Cleanup\n438:     };\n439:   }, []);\n440: \n441:   // 4. EVENT HANDLERS (with useCallback for passed handlers)\n442:   const handleItemSelect = useCallback((itemId: string) => {\n443:     setSelectedItem(itemId);\n444:   }, []);\n445: \n446:   const handleSave = useCallback(async () => {\n447:     try {\n448:       // Save logic\n449:       onComplete?.();\n450:     } catch (error) {\n451:       console.error('Failed to save:', error);\n452:     }\n453:   }, [onComplete]);\n454: \n455:   // 5. RENDER\n456:   return (\n457:     <Card className=\"w-full max-w-md\">\n458:       <CardHeader>\n459:         <h2 className=\"text-xl font-bold\">My Component</h2>\n460:       </CardHeader>\n461:       <CardContent className=\"space-y-4\">\n462:         <p className={cn('text-muted-foreground', loading && 'opacity-50')}>\n463:           {user?.email}\n464:         </p>\n465:         <Button onClick={handleSave} disabled={loading}>\n466:           {loading ? 'Loading...' : 'Save'}\n467:         </Button>\n468:       </CardContent>\n469:     </Card>\n470:   );\n471: }\n472: ```\n473: \n474: ---\n475: \n476: ## Component Separation\n477: \n478: ### When to Split Components\n479: \n480: **Split into multiple components when:**\n481: \n482: - Component exceeds 200 lines\n483: - Multiple distinct responsibilities\n484: - Reusable sections\n485: - Complex nested JSX\n486: \n487: **Example:**\n488: \n489: ```typescript\n490: // ❌ AVOID - Monolithic\n491: function MassivePage() {\n492:   // 500+ lines\n493:   // Header logic\n494:   // Form logic\n495:   // Table logic\n496:   // Modal logic\n497: }\n498: \n499: // ✅ PREFERRED - Modular\n500: function Page() {\n501:   return (\n502:     <div className=\"space-y-6\">\n503:       <PageHeader />\n504:       <SearchForm onSearch={handleSearch} />\n505:       <DataTable data={filteredData} />\n506:       <ActionModal open={isOpen} onClose={handleClose} />\n507:     </div>\n508:   );\n509: }\n510: ```\n511: \n512: ### When to Keep Together\n513: \n514: **Keep in same file when:**\n515: \n516: - Component < 100 lines\n517: - Tightly coupled logic\n518: - Not reusable elsewhere\n519: - Simple presentation component\n520: \n521: ---\n522: \n523: ## Lazy Loading Pattern\n524: \n525: ### When to Lazy Load\n526: \n527: Lazy load components that are:\n528: \n529: - Heavy (DataGrid, charts, rich text editors)\n530: - Route-level components\n531: - Modal/dialog content (not shown initially)\n532: - Below-the-fold content\n533: \n534: ### How to Lazy Load\n535: \n536: ```typescript\n537: import { lazy, Suspense } from 'react';\n538: \n539: // Lazy load heavy component\n540: const HeavyEditor = lazy(() => import('./HeavyEditor'));\n541: \n542: // Usage with Suspense\n543: function Page() {\n544:   return (\n545:     <Suspense fallback={<div>Loading...</div>}>\n546:       <HeavyEditor />\n547:     </Suspense>\n548:   );\n549: }\n550: ```\n551: \n552: ---\n553: \n554: ## Component Communication\n555: \n556: ### Props Down, Events Up\n557: \n558: ```typescript\n559: // Parent\n560: function Parent() {\n561:   const [selectedId, setSelectedId] = useState<string | null>(null);\n562: \n563:   return (\n564:     <Child\n565:       data={data} // Props down\n566:       onSelect={setSelectedId} // Events up\n567:     />\n568:   );\n569: }\n570: \n571: // Child\n572: interface ChildProps {\n573:   data: Data[];\n574:   onSelect: (id: string) => void;\n575: }\n576: \n577: export default function Child({ data, onSelect }: ChildProps) {\n578:   return (\n579:     <ul>\n580:       {data.map((item) => (\n581:         <li key={item.id} onClick={() => onSelect(item.id)}>\n582:           {item.name}\n583:         </li>\n584:       ))}\n585:     </ul>\n586:   );\n587: }\n588: ```\n589: \n590: ### Using Redux for Shared State\n591: \n592: ```typescript\n593: // When state needs to be shared across components\n594: import { useAppDispatch, useAppSelector } from '~/redux/store/hooks';\n595: import { selectItem } from '~/redux/features/itemSlice';\n596: \n597: function Child() {\n598:   const dispatch = useAppDispatch();\n599:   const selectedId = useAppSelector((state) => state.item.selectedId);\n600: \n601:   const handleSelect = (id: string) => {\n602:     dispatch(selectItem(id));\n603:   };\n604: \n605:   return <div onClick={() => handleSelect('123')}>Select</div>;\n606: }\n607: ```\n608: \n609: ---\n610: \n611: ## Summary\n612: \n613: **Modern Component Recipe:**\n614: \n615: 1. Function components with TypeScript props interface\n616: 2. Shadcn/UI components from `~/components/ui/`\n617: 3. `cn()` utility for conditional classes\n618: 4. Tailwind CSS for styling\n619: 5. `useAppSelector` and `useAppDispatch` for Redux\n620: 6. Event handlers with `useCallback` when passed to children\n621: 7. Default export at bottom\n622: \n623: ---\n624: \n625: ## MANDATORY: Async State Handling\n626: \n627: Every component that fetches data MUST handle all three states:\n628: \n629: ```typescript\n630: // MANDATORY: Loading state\n631: if (isLoading) return <LoadingSkeleton />;\n632: \n633: // MANDATORY: Error state\n634: if (error) return <ErrorState message={error.message} onRetry={refetch} />;\n635: \n636: // MANDATORY: Empty state (distinct from error)\n637: if (!data?.length) return <EmptyState title=\"No items found\" />;\n638: \n639: // Happy path\n640: return <DataList items={data} />;\n641: ```\n642: \n643: **Rules:**\n644: - Loading skeleton (not spinner) for initial data loads\n645: - Error state with retry button for API failures\n646: - Empty state for zero results (NOT the same component as error)\n647: - Error boundaries wrapping route-level components for uncaught errors\n648: \n649: ## MANDATORY: No Business Logic in Components\n650: \n651: Components must only handle rendering and event delegation:\n652: \n653: ```typescript\n654: // BAD: Business logic in component\n655: const filteredUsers = users.filter(u => u.role === 'admin' && u.isActive);\n656: const sortedUsers = filteredUsers.sort((a, b) => a.name.localeCompare(b.name));\n657: \n658: // GOOD: Logic in selector/utility\n659: const activeAdmins = useAppSelector(selectActiveAdmins);\n660: ```\n661: \n662: **See Also:**\n663: \n664: - [styling-guide.md](styling-guide.md) - Tailwind CSS patterns\n665: - [common-patterns.md](common-patterns.md) - Form patterns\n666: - [complete-examples.md](complete-examples.md) - Full working examples\n\n(End of file - total 666 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Component Patterns\n\nModern component architecture using Shadcn/UI, Tailwind CSS, and TypeScript.\n\n---\n\n## Function Component Pattern (PREFERRED)\n\n### Why Function Components\n\nAll components use function components with TypeScript for:\n\n- Explicit type safety for props\n- Consistent component signatures\n- Clear prop interface documentation\n- Better IDE autocomplete\n\n### Basic Pattern\n\n```typescript","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":".claude/react/docs/component-patterns.md","time":{"start":1779196966463,"end":1779196966787}},"id":"prt_e406730b7001AQgXtHF9EOFfxO","sessionID":"ses_1bf9f8fabffeWrpKfONbqDLERZ","messageID":"msg_e40665684001CLexdMdAguT4AF"}}
